  "Question": "<p>I am interesting in the proof of that every rational number cannot have in decimal form infinite number of digits that don't repeat (or the other way around).</p> <p>So, then is enough to prove following statement: <em>For any <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_727\"><math alttext=\"n\\in\\mathbb{N}\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>\u2208</mo><mi>\u2115</mi></mrow></semantics></math></span> rational number <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_728\"><math alttext=\"\\frac{1}{n}\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>n</mi></mfrac></semantics></math></span> can be represented in decimal form such that it's digits, if there are infinitely many, are repeating.</em></p> <p>If this is true, then it is true for any <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_729\"><math alttext=\"\\frac{m}{n}=\\frac{1}{n}+\\frac{1}{n}+...+\\frac{1}{n}\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mfrac><mi>m</mi><mi>n</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>n</mi></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>n</mi></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">\u2026</mi><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>n</mi></mfrac></mrow></mrow></semantics></math></span> (<span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_730\"><math alttext=\"m\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mi>m</mi></semantics></math></span> times).</p>",
  "Title": "Why decimals of rational numbers behave periodically?",
